'''Mandara-ji''' (曼荼羅寺) is a temple of the {{ill|Shingon Zentsuji Sect|ja|真言宗善通寺派|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Zentsuji|ja|善通寺市|12=draft}}, Kagawa Prefecture, Japan. It is the 72nd temple in the {{ill|Shikoku Pilgrimage|ja|四国八十八箇所|12=draft}}. The temple is also known as Gabai-shi-zan Enmei-in (我拜師山延命院). Its principal image is {{ill|Kongokai Dainichi Nyorai|ja|金剛界大日如来|12=draft}}.
* '''Mantra''': "On Abiraunken Basaradatoban" * '''Go-eika''' (pilgrimage song): "Even a glance at the Mandala shall free one from returning twice or thrice again."
== History == According to temple tradition, Mandara-ji was founded in 596 CE as a clan temple of the {{ill|Saeki Clan|ja|佐伯氏|12=draft}}, the family of {{ill|Kūkai|ja|空海|12=draft}} (Kōbō Daishi). Originally known as '''Seisaka-ji''' (世坂寺), the temple was later re-established by Kūkai after his return from Tang China. He enshrined the {{ill|Mandala of the Two Realms|ja|両界曼荼羅|12=draft}} and dedicated the main image of Dainichi Nyorai in honor of his mother, {{ill|Tamayori Gozen|ja|玉依御前|12=draft}}. The temple was then renamed Mandara-ji.
During the Kamakura period, the temple prospered, receiving territorial grants from {{ill|Emperor Go-Horikawa|ja|後堀河天皇|12=draft}}. However, the temple suffered destruction during the wars of the Sengoku period, including a fire set by Miyoshi Jitsunaga in 1560. It was later restored during the early Edo period.
The temple's famous "Kasamatsu" (umbrella pine), said to have been planted by Kūkai, was cut down in 2002 due to damage from pine wilt disease.
== Buildings == [[File:Mandaraji okunoin 01.jpg|thumb|From the precincts of Mandara-ji, the former Oku-no-in of {{ill|Shusshaka-ji|ja|出釈迦寺|12=draft}} can be seen.]] * '''Main Gate''' (仁王門) * '''Main Hall''': The principal image of Dainichi Nyorai is displayed annually during the spring equinox. * '''Daishi Hall''': Dedicated to Kūkai, where his image can be worshipped. * '''Kannon Hall''': Houses a standing statue of Sho Kannon (Prefectural Cultural Property) and a golden image of Dainichi Nyorai. * '''Goma Hall''': Features a central seated statue of Fudō Myōō and smaller wooden statues of the Five Great Myōō. * '''Hachiman Shrine''': Reconstructed in 1990, includes a main and worship hall. * '''Jizō Hall''': Contains a small painted standing statue of Jizō Bosatsu. * '''Aizen Hall''': A small vermillion shrine dedicated to Aizen Myōō. * Other structures include various Jizō statues, a stone Dainichi Nyorai, and a Fukurokuju statue.
The precincts include the "Sleeping Stone of Saigyō" and a related memorial stone inscribed with a poem attributed to him. A paid parking area is available near the main gate.
== Cultural Properties == === Kagawa Prefecture Designated Tangible Cultural Property === * '''Wooden Standing Statue of Sho Kannon''': Designated in 1955 (Showa 30). Late Heian period.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pref.kagawa.lg.jp/kenkyoui/shogaigakushu/bunkazai/culturalassets/culturalassets_3.html |title=Cultural Assets in Kagawa |access-date=2023-06-28 |publisher=Kagawa Prefecture}}</ref>
== Access == ; By Train * 4.5 km from {{ill|Zentsuji Station|ja|善通寺駅|12=draft}} (JR Shikoku Dosan Line) ; By Road * 0.5 km from {{ill|Kagawa Prefectural Route 48|ja|香川県道48号善通寺詫間線|12=draft}} * 6.2 km from {{ill|Zentsuji Interchange|ja|善通寺インターチェンジ|12=draft}} (Takamatsu Expressway)
== Nearby Temples == ; {{ill|Shikoku Pilgrimage|ja|四国八十八箇所|12=draft}} : 71 {{ill|Iwayaji|ja|弥谷寺|12=draft}} -- (3.5 km) -* '''72 Mandara-ji''' -- (0.5 km) -- 73 {{ill|Shusshaka-ji|ja|出釈迦寺|12=draft}}
